Clarify that you might need -Dusemultiplicity

on our way to first class hashes

Wait for server startup to avoid 599

This patch avoids a race condition while testing whereby our request
would fire previously to the server actually starting.

With this approach we should have guarantees that our server is up and
running before the Proc::Async passes back to the callsite.

Also, kill the server after we run the tests.

commit_list.message:
CC values now transmitting from rotaries/encoders

The Push sends its encoder values in a relative format already ( 1+n is
turned right, 128 - n is turned left, where n is a value that increases
with the speed of the turn ). These values now show up on  'rotary rel'
param outputs.

All other new parameters are not yet functional.

commit_list.message:
initial git-ification

It's time to have this under proper version control.

Current features:

- 'clear pads' : attach a trigger and it does what it says (make sure
you connect the midi out and have your rack devices set properly)
- pad color value arrays : use the array with a value mapper and the
commatext with a combobox, and you can select colors values you can send
with 'create midi message' modules in your own patch

- 'touch rotaries' : you have trigger outputs for each rotary

commit_list.message:
Once again re-aligning after a misunderstanding

In fact nodes should be Leafs until the point where they would become
TwoNode's. This is in contrast to promoting them while having their
Leafs be empty. So, a TwoNode should always have a $!d1 and nodes l/r
with at least one $!d1 as well.

With any luck, this is my last cockup :)

commit_list.message:
Fully functioning up till ThreeNode

This marks a significant advance in the TwoThree tree, inasmuch as nodes
now morph cleanly between each other and we are bumping right up against
the breakthrough of ThreeNodes. After that our tree will have...
branches!

The big thing I learned in this commit was the ($SELF is rw : ... )
signature syntax. I must have seen it before, but now it makes sense :)
This gives you the container of 'self', which is what you need if you
want to, for instance, replace its contents with something else.

This is not likely to be a very nice thing to do for external users, so
the API is being thought of only in terms of what Tree will provide. The
rest will be lexical classes which remain internal to Tree.

commit_list.message:
Buff up the SIGINT handler

If we die in the sigint handler we can be rest assured that all the relevant
supplies will be chopped off and we will really exit at the time that
the user so explicitly requested.

This also moves the $!print-enabled pattern from the Terminal::Print
object to its grids. This should avoid race conditions (due to
OO::Monitors) as well as keeping it a bit cleaner in my opinion.

Later, we can harden these cases so that you can't double disable a grid,
maybe throw an exception when trying to print to a disabled grid.

commit_list.message:
Significant re-working of internal printing

This commit shifts the determination of 'ansi' or 'universal' printing
modes to run time. There is now a subset,
Terminal::Print::MoveCursorProfile, that is utilized for safeguarding
the constructors for both Terminal::Print and Terminal::Print::Grid. We
enable 'ansi' by default. This  subset will be exported into any
namespace which imports Terminal::Print::Commands.

Thanks to nine++ for pointing towards a better API that allows the
Terminal::Print user to choose a profile at run time. A program could
offer a debug or setup mode that would prompt the user with a test
movement and then ask or confirmation that it worked. If not, re-create
as 'universal'.

Meanwhile, I promised up the .change-cell and .print-cell methods in a
way that should a) remain transparent at the API level, and b) seems to
me to actually be quite a bit smoother/faster at printing. I'm curious
to hear whether this might be the case for others.
